5f4a5a4e-a2f3-45a1-befb-ad5ec7fb07b9	dilution_calculator	Andara Dilution Calculator – Find Your Sulfate Activation Range	/tools/dilution-calculator	tool	tool_calculator	shop	shop_overview	4	\N	<p>Tool · Andara Ionic Mineral Sulfates</p><h1>Andara Dilution Calculator – find your sulfate activation range</h1><p>Calculate how many drops or milliliters of Andara Ionic Mineral Sulfates you need to bring your water into the <strong>sulfate activation range</strong>. This page helps you align your water with the <strong>Andara activation zone</strong> of approximately <strong>17–30&nbsp;mg sulfate per liter</strong>, so you can explore <strong>clarity, flocculation and structured-water behaviour</strong> in a repeatable way.</p><ul><li><p><strong>Find your dose in seconds</strong> – enter water volume and target sulfate level, get a suggested Andara dose (ml / drops) for that range.</p></li><li><p><strong>Understand the science</strong> – see how the <strong>sulfate activation band</strong> overlaps with biology, lab tests and classical water treatment.</p></li><li><p><strong>Use preset scenarios</strong> – jugs, carafes, lab flasks and plant-watering dilutions.</p></li></ul><p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" class="text-accent underline andara-hero__cta andara-hero__cta--primary" href="#andara-dilution-calculator"> Start dilution calculation</a></p><p>Prefer background theory? <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" class="text-accent underline andara-hero__support-link" href="/science/water/ez-water">Read about structured water and sulfate activation</a></p><p>Visual placeholder: A clean interface mockup of the dilution calculator on a laptop and phone, with a bottle of “Andara Ionic – Primordial Ionic Sulphate Minerals” and a jug of clear water beside it.</p><p> The Andara Dilution Calculator helps you tune your water into the sulfate activation range for clarity and structured-water behaviour.</p><h2>How the Andara sulfate activation range works</h2><p>Andara Ionic Mineral Sulfates are designed to operate in a small but powerful band: <strong>about 17–30&nbsp;mg sulfate per liter of water</strong>. In this window, water often shows a shift toward <strong>clarity, flocculation and more ordered hydration layers</strong>, echoing what we see in mineral springs, plasma sulfate levels and classical water treatment.</p><h3>Biological reference (~30&nbsp;mg/L)</h3><p>Human plasma naturally holds sulfate around <strong>30&nbsp;mg/L</strong>. At this level, sulfated surfaces support <strong>hydration layers</strong> and structured water at cell interfaces. This biological reference point helps us understand what a “reasonable” sulfate level looks like in living systems.</p><h3>Lab reference (~17–18&nbsp;mg/L)</h3><p>In the Aurmina / Adya lineage of lab tests, adding about <strong>1&nbsp;ml mineral stock per 1&nbsp;liter of water</strong> contributes roughly <strong>17–18&nbsp;mg/L sulfate</strong>. At this dose, UV measurements (e.g. around 270&nbsp;nm) often show <strong>structured-water signatures</strong> linked to exclusion-zone behaviour.</p><h3>Water-treatment reference (10–35&nbsp;mg/L)</h3><p>Classical water treatment uses sulfate-forming coagulants in a similar window: <strong>about 10–35&nbsp;mg/L sulfate</strong>. In this band, particles flocculate, turbidity drops and the water reorganises into finer hydration clusters.</p><p>The Andara Dilution Calculator uses these overlapping references to suggest <strong>everyday exploratory dilutions</strong> for household water, lab setups or plant-watering experiments – always without making medical or therapeutic claims.</p><h2>Andara Dilution Calculator – interactive dose suggestion</h2><p>Use this calculator to estimate how much Andara Ionic Mineral Sulfates to add to your water to reach a target sulfate level. The numbers are based on a working assumption that <strong>1&nbsp;ml Andara stock per 1&nbsp;liter of water ≈ 17–18&nbsp;mg/L sulfate</strong>. Results are for <strong>educational and experimental water work only</strong>.</p><p>1. Enter your water volume</p><p>Water volume (liters)</p><p>2. Choose your target sulfate level</p><p>Target sulfate level (mg/L)</p><p>Suggested range: <strong>17–30&nbsp;mg/L</strong> (Andara activation range)</p><p>3. Drop size / bottle info (optional)</p><p>Approximate drop volume (ml per drop)</p><p>If you leave this empty, the calculator can return only ml values.</p><p> Calculate suggested Andara dose</p><h3>Suggested Andara dose (example placeholder)</h3><p>For <strong>1.0&nbsp;liter</strong> of water and a target of <strong>18&nbsp;mg/L sulfate</strong>, an approximate suggestion would be:</p><ul><li><p><strong>1.0&nbsp;ml</strong> Andara Ionic Mineral Sulfates stock</p></li><li><p>≈ <strong>20 drops</strong> (if one drop is about 0.05&nbsp;ml – adjust to your actual drop volume)</p></li></ul><p>This example result is static text – connect your own JavaScript or Next.js logic to populate this box dynamically using the input fields above.</p><h3>How the calculation works (conceptual)</h3><p>The calculator uses a simple proportional model where <strong>1&nbsp;ml stock per liter ≈ 17.5&nbsp;mg/L sulfate</strong>.</p><p><strong>Example:</strong><br>If you want <strong>21&nbsp;mg/L sulfate</strong> in 1&nbsp;liter of water:</p><ul><li><p>Required dose (ml) ≈ target_mg_per_l / 17.5.<br>So 21 / 17.5 ≈ <strong>1.2&nbsp;ml per liter</strong>.</p></li><li><p>For 2&nbsp;liters, multiply by volume → ~2.4&nbsp;ml total.</p></li></ul><p>This is a working educational model, not a strict analytical measurement. For precise sulfate levels, use lab testing.</p><h3>Important note</h3><p>This tool is for <strong>water clarification and structuring experiments</strong>. It does not provide medical dosing, health advice or therapeutic guidance. Use at your own discretion and always respect local regulations.</p><h2>Quick dilution presets – Andara sulfate activation examples</h2><p>Prefer ready-made suggestions? Use these <strong>example dilution presets</strong> to get a feeling for the Andara activation range in everyday scenarios – carafes, water jugs, lab flasks and plant-watering.</p><p> Example dilutions assuming 1&nbsp;ml Andara stock ≈ 17.5&nbsp;mg sulfate per liter of water. Use case Water volume Target sulfate (mg/L) Approx. Andara dose (ml) Approx. drops* Notes Small glass 0.25&nbsp;L 18&nbsp;mg/L 0.26&nbsp;ml ≈ 5 drops Micro-test; best for tasting and simple visual observation. Water carafe 1.0&nbsp;L 18&nbsp;mg/L 1.0&nbsp;ml ≈ 20 drops Everyday Andara test; observe flocculation and clarity changes. Household jug 2.0&nbsp;L 21&nbsp;mg/L 2.4&nbsp;ml ≈ 48 drops Good for family water jugs; allow settling before pouring. Lab flask 1.0&nbsp;L 25&nbsp;mg/L 1.4&nbsp;ml ≈ 28 drops Useful for pH / ORP / EC tracking experiments. Plant watering 5.0&nbsp;L 18&nbsp;mg/L 5.0&nbsp;ml ≈ 100 drops Applied to soil/watering can for structural water experiments.</p><p>*Drop counts assume ~0.05&nbsp;ml per drop. Adjust according to your actual dropper.</p><h2>Frequently asked questions about Andara dilutions</h2><h3>Are these dilution values medical dosages?</h3><p>No. These numbers are <strong>not medical dosages</strong>. They are conceptual, water-focused suggestions based on sulfate chemistry and the Andara activation range. The entire page is intended for <strong>water clarification, structuring and lab-style experiments</strong>, not for health treatments.</p><h3>Why is the Andara activation range 17–30&nbsp;mg/L sulfate?</h3><p>This window is where <strong>three independent domains overlap</strong>: biological plasma sulfate (~30&nbsp;mg/L), lab measurements for structured water (~17–18&nbsp;mg/L at 1&nbsp;ml/L dose) and classical drinking-water treatment (~10–35&nbsp;mg/L sulfate for flocculation and clarification).</p><h3>How precise are the mg/L numbers?</h3><p>They are <strong>working approximations</strong> based on the mineral profile and literature. For laboratory-grade precision, you would confirm sulfate levels using appropriate analytical methods. The calculator and table are tools for <strong>relative tuning</strong> and exploration rather than absolute measurement.</p><h3>Do I always need to aim for the activation range?</h3><p>Not necessarily. It is a <strong>reference band</strong> where a lot of the interesting behaviour appears. You can explore lower or higher dilutions depending on your experiments, while keeping in mind that everything here is framed around <strong>water chemistry and structure</strong>, not medical applications.</p><h2>Next steps – explore the science behind your dilution</h2><p>Every dilution you create is connected to a <strong>deeper Andara science story</strong> – from structured water to sulfate chemistry and crystalline matrices.</p><h3>Water &amp; EZ structures</h3><p>Learn how <strong>EZ water and hydration layers</strong> form at charged mineral surfaces and how the sulfate activation range supports this behaviour.</p><p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" class="text-accent underline" href="/science/water/ez-water">Go to EZ water science</a></p><h3>Sulfate &amp; flocculation</h3><p>Explore how <strong>ionic sulfate minerals</strong> influence flocculation, turbidity and redox parameters in water – from lab flasks to household jugs.</p><p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" class="text-accent underline" href="/science/minerals/sulfate-chemistry">Go to sulfate chemistry</a></p><h3>Crystalline matrix &amp; charge</h3><p>See how the <strong>tetrahedral/hexagonal crystalline matrix</strong> of ionic sulfates interacts with water, ions and bioelectric fields.</p><p><a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer nofollow" class="text-accent underline" href="/science/crystalline/overview">Go to crystalline matrix</a></p>	ionic sulfate dilution calculator	\N	\N	\N	\N	published	{}	\N	2025-12-08 03:00:05.427572	2025-12-08 09:08:55.538	\N	\N	\N	[]	[]	\N	\N	\N
