ity is a core goal of the Andara framework."}, {"id": "value_prop", "kind": "text", "title": "The Andara Perspective: Voltage as the Organizing Field of Life", "content": "Andara views life as a **voltage-driven phenomenon** supported by minerals, structured water, crystalline matrices and natural electromagnetic fields.\\n\\nBioelectricity is not just a medical topic — it is the **foundation of vitality**, influencing:\\n\\n- hydration\\n- detoxification\\n- cellular repair\\n- enzyme activation\\n- mitochondrial energy production\\n- emotional and mental clarity\\n- coherence of the entire terrain\\n\\nIn this framework:\\n\\n- Minerals provide **charge carriers** (ions)\\n- Structured water creates **charge separation and storage**\\n- Crystalline matrices act as **waveguides and signal paths**\\n- Coherent EMF environments support **field integrity**\\n\\nAndara Ionic Sulphate Minerals are designed to support this electrical terrain by providing ionic mineral fields that integrate with water, tissue and soil."}, {"id": "fundamentals", "kind": "text", "title": "Bioelectric Fundamentals: How Cells Generate and Maintain Voltage", "content": "Cells maintain voltage through **ion gradients** across their membranes.\\n\\nKey players:\\n\\n- **Sodium (Na+)** and **Potassium (K+)** → create resting membrane potentials.\\n- **Calcium (Ca2+)** → triggers signaling, contraction and regeneration.\\n- **Chloride (Cl-)** → stabilizes electrical gradients.\\n- **Magnesium (Mg2+)** → regulates ATP (the body's electrical currency).\\n- **Protons (H+)** → drive mitochondrial energy production.\\n\\nTogether, these ions create a resting membrane potential of **-70 to -90 mV** in healthy cells.\\n\\nWhen voltage drops, cells lose:\\n\\n- repair capacity\\n- signaling clarity\\n- detoxification efficiency\\n- resilience to stress\\n\\nBioelectricity is the **language cells use to coordinate** life itself."}, {"id": "structured_water", "kind": "text", "title": "Structured Water: The Electrical Engine Fueling Every Cell", "content": "**Structured water (EZ-water)** behaves like a **liquid crystal battery**, capable of holding charge and separating ions.\\n\\nExperiments show that structured water layers can:\\n\\n- separate charge (creating electrical potential)\\n- store electrons\\n- expand in response to infrared light\\n- form coherent electromagnetic domains\\n\\nThis liquid crystalline behavior is essential for:\\n\\n- nutrient absorption\\n- waste removal\\n- nerve conduction\\n- mitochondrial ATP generation\\n- fascia signaling\\n\\nAndara minerals **prepare water** for this structuring by introducing ionic sulphate fields that support geometric ordering and coherence."}, {"id": "minerals", "kind": "text", "title": "Minerals: The Charge Carriers That Make Bioelectricity Possible", "content": "Minerals are the **electrolytes** of life — the ions that conduct charge through water and tissue.\\n\\nImportant examples:\\n\\n- **Sodium-Potassium pump** → maintains resting membrane potential.\\n- **Magnesium** → stabilizes ATP, allowing energy reactions.\\n- **Calcium** → acts as an electrical switch.\\n- **Sulphate (SO4 2-)** → shapes hydration shells, detox phases and structural coherence.\\n\\nWhen minerals are depleted, bioelectricity becomes weak, chaotic or unbalanced. Cell communication falters. Energy production drops. Terrain coherence suffers.\\n\\nAndara Ionic Sulphate Minerals offer a **broad-spectrum, ionic mineral field** designed to support the electrical terrain of water, body and soil."}, {"id": "fascia_network", "kind": "text", "title": "Fascia & Liquid Crystals: The Body's Superconductive Communication Network", "content": "Fascia — the connective tissue web — is not passive wrapping. It is a **liquid crystal semiconductor** capable of transmitting:\\n\\n- mechanical force\\n- electrical currents\\n- proton flow\\n- biophotons\\n- subtle electromagnetic information\\n\\nFascia links the entire body into one **continuous electrical network**, influencing:\\n\\n- posture\\n- emotional states\\n- energy flow\\n- cellular repair\\n- movement efficiency\\n\\nWhen fascia is hydrated with **structured, mineralized water**, it becomes:\\n\\n- more conductive\\n- more coherent\\n- more responsive\\n\\nAndara water and mineral strategies are designed to support **fascia-friendly terrains**."}, {"id": "mitochondria", "kind": "text", "title": "Mitochondria: Charge Factories Powered by Proton Flow", "content": "Mitochondria generate ATP through the **electron transport chain**, which is essentially a **voltage-driven process**.\\n\\nThey create charge through:\\n\\n- proton gradients\\n- electron movement\\n- structured water layers lining the membranes\\n\\nHealthy mitochondria generate around **150-180 mV** of membrane voltage.\\n\\nWhen voltage falls:\\n\\n- energy drops\\n- detox slows\\n- oxidative stress increases\\n- regeneration halts\\n\\nBioelectricity is therefore inseparable from **energy production and metabolic resilience**."}, {"id": "terrain_model", "kind": "text", "title": "The Electrical Terrain: pH, Charge and Regenerative Capacity", "content": "pH is not just chemistry — it is **electrical potential of hydrogen (H+)**.\\n\\nTerrain coherence depends on:\\n\\n- stable membrane potentials\\n- balanced electrolytes\\n- structured water phases\\n- mineral crystals guiding the field\\n- detox pathways maintaining clarity\\n\\nA well-ordered terrain has:\\n\\n- strong voltage\\n- coherent hydration\\n- efficient detoxification\\n- high adaptability\\n\\nA collapsed terrain has:\\n\\n- low voltage\\n- chaotic water\\n- sluggish detox\\n- low resilience\\n\\nAndara works to support **electrically coherent terrains** through mineral, water and crystalline strategies."}, {"id": "applications", "kind": "list", "title": "Bioelectric Applications in Daily Life, Water, and Terrain", "content": {"items": [{"label": "Structured & Mineralized Drinking Water", "description": "Water with coherent structure and ionic minerals supports membrane potentials, hydration, and electron flow."}, {"label": "Terrain Support & Natural Regeneration", "description": "Voltage-friendly minerals and structured water help the terrain maintain clarity and resilience."}, {"label": "Movement, Breath & Fascia Activation", "description": "Physical activity stimulates piezoelectric charge in fascia, raising voltage naturally."}, {"label": "Soil Bioelectric Health", "description": "Minerals and structured water promote microbial vitality and nutrient exchange in agricultural soils."}, {"label": "Spa & Hydrotherapy", "description": "Mineral-rich, structured water enhances sensory and energetic coherence in bathing environments."}]}}, {"id": "future_pages", "kind": "list", "title": "Future Andara Library Pages Expanding the Bioelectricity Topic", "content": {"items": [{"label": "Cellular Voltage & Regeneration", "description": "Deep dive into how voltage directs wound healing, tissue repair, and growth processes."}, {"label": "Fascia as a Liquid Crystal Network", "description": "Exploring the conductive, bio-photonic and structural intelligence of fascia."}, {"label": "Mitochondria & Proton Gradients", "description": "Understanding how charge drives energy production and resilience."}, {"label": "Bioelectric Soil Systems", "description": "How microbial networks and mineral structures generate electrical fields in healthy soil."}, {"label": "Voltage Collapse & Environmental Stressors", "description": "How EMF, toxins, stress and dehydration degrade voltage and coherence."}]}}, {"id": "faq", "kind": "faq", "title": "Frequently Asked Questions About Bioelectricity", "content": {"items": [{"answer": "Yes. Membrane potentials, ion flows, proton gradients, pH, voltage differences across tissues and conductive fascia responses can all be measured scientifically.", "question": "Is bioelectricity measurable?"}, {"answer": "Structured water can support charge separation, hydration, ionic mobility and fascia conductivity — all key contributors to strong terrain voltage.", "question": "Can structured water increase voltage?"}, {"answer": "Absolutely. Without minerals acting as charge carriers, the body's electrical system cannot function. This includes sodium, potassium, magnesium, calcium, chloride and sulphate.", "question": "Are minerals necessary for bioelectricity?"}, {"answer": "This page focuses on measurable electrical processes. However, many traditions interpret bioelectric fields as part of a broader energetic system. The two perspectives can coexist without contradiction.", "question": "Is bioelectricity the same as metaphysical energy?"}]}}, {"id": "cta_section", "kind": "cta", "title": "Strengthen Your Voltage. Strengthen Your Terrain.", "content": {"text": "Bioelectricity is the foundation of vitality. When your water is structured, your minerals are balanced, your tissues are conductive and your terrain is coherent, your voltage rises — and life flows.\\n\\nAndara Ionic Sulphate Minerals support this field by conditioning water and terrain with ionic, balanced, primordial minerals. Begin reinforcing your voltage blueprint today.", "buttonLabel": "Explore Andara Ionic Sulphate Minerals"}}], "relatedPages": [{"slug": "water-science", "title": "Water Science", "reason": "Structured water stores charge and enables ion movement"}, {"slug": "mineral-science", "title": "Mineral Science", "reason": "Electrolyte minerals are the charge carriers of bioelectricity"}, {"slug": "crystalline-matrix", "title": "Crystalline Matrix", "reason": "Fascia liquid crystals conduct electrical signals"}, {"slug": "terrain-model", "title": "Terrain Model", "reason": "Voltage is the governing force of terrain health"}, {"slug": "sulphur-sulphate-pathways", "title": "Sulphate Pathways", "reason": "Sulphate ions carry charge and support membrane potentials"}, {"slug": "liquid-crystal-biology", "title": "Liquid Crystal Biology", "reason": "Liquid crystals conduct bioelectricity through fascia, membranes and ECM"}]}}	\N	2025-12-08 03:00:05.701238	2025-12-08 06:38:48.165	\N	\N	\N	[]	["bioelectricity", "cellular voltage", "membrane potential", "ion channels", "terrain model", "structured water", "EZ-water", "ionic sulphate minerals", "electrolytes", "proton gradients", "mitochondrial charge", "fascia conductivity", "liquid crystal biology", "biofield", "Andara terrain coherence"]	\N	\N	\N
d2bcc865-bde2-42e3-aa75-cdb39bf74130	science_mineral_comparison_overview	Mineral Sources – Comparing Ocean, Plant, Fulvic, Salt & Mica	/science/mineral-sources	page	cluster_overview	mineral_sources	science_library_overview	9	\N	\N	mineral source comparison	\N	\N	\N	\N	published	{}	\N	2025-12-08 03:00:05.805029	2025-12-09 10:28:11.756	\N	\N	\N	[]	[]	{"pageId": "science_mineral_comparison_overview", "cluster": "mineral_sources", "priority": "P1", "vibeKeywords": ["cosmic", "earth", "ocean", "forest", "crystal", "volcanic"], "aiImagePrompt": "A split-screen cosmic illustration showing five mineral worlds: deep ocean, green plants and seaweed, dark humic soil, pink salt crystals, and glowing volcanic black mica crystal transforming into structured water, in indigo, turquoise, emerald, and gold tones, high detail, cinematic lighting, Andara style.", "aiVideoPrompt": "Subtle looping animation of water flowing through five scenes: ocean currents, kelp forest, dark soil breathing, salt crystals dissolving, and a volcanic spring lighting up into hexagonal structured water, with soft camera drift and particle glows.", "designerNotes": "Use this page as a core explainer: calm, educational, yet visually rich. Emphasize comparison and clarity. Every section should feel like a distinct 'temple' of minerals with its own mood, but united by Andara color language.", "emotionalTone": ["clarity", "awe", "trust", "groundedness"], "animationIdeas": ["slow water ripples", "floating mineral icons", "crystalline shimmer", "scroll fade-up", "parallax strata layers"]}	<!--\nANDARA VISUAL CONFIG:\npageId: "mineral-sources-comparison"\ncluster: "Science Library – Mineral Science"\npriority: "P1"\nvibeKeywords: ["cosmic", "earth", "ocean", "forest", "crystal", "volcanic"]\nemotionalTone: ["clarity", "awe", "trust", "groundedness"]\nanimationIdeas: ["slow water ripples", "floating mineral icons", "crystalline shimmer", "scroll fade-up", "parallax strata layers"]\naiImagePromptHero: "A split-screen cosmic illustration showing five mineral worlds: deep ocean, green plants and seaweed, dark humic soil, pink salt crystals, and glowing volcanic black mica crystal transforming into structured water, in indigo, turquoise, emerald, and gold tones, high detail, cinematic lighting, Andara style."\naiVideoPromptHero: "Subtle looping animation of water flowing through five scenes: ocean currents, kelp forest, dark soil breathing, salt crystals dissolving, and a volcanic spring lighting up into hexagonal structured water, with soft camera drift and particle glows."\ndesignerNotes: "Use this page as a core explainer: calm, educational, yet visually rich. Emphasize comparison and clarity. Every section should feel like a distinct 'temple' of minerals with its own mood, but united by Andara color language."\n-->\n\n<main\n  id="mineral-sources-page"\n  class="andara-page andara-page--science"\n  aria-label="Mineral Sources – Comparing Ocean, Plant, Fulvic, Salt and Mica"\n>\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       HERO – MINERAL GATEWAYS\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-sources-hero"\n    class="andara-hero andara-hero--science"\n    aria-label="Mineral Sources Overview Hero"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-hero__inner">\n      <header class="andara-hero__content">\n        <p class="andara-hero__label">\n          Mineral Science · Source Comparison\n        </p>\n        <h1 class="andara-hero__headline">\n          Mineral Sources – Comparing Ocean, Plant, Fulvic, Salt &amp; Volcanic Mica\n        </h1>\n        <p class="andara-hero__subline">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            Five different faces of the same Earth, five different ways minerals speak to water and life.\n          </span>\n          We explore how <strong>ocean water</strong>, <strong>plants &amp; seaweeds</strong>,\n          <strong>fulvic/humic complexes</strong>, <strong>sea salts</strong>, and\n          <strong>volcanic sulfate minerals</strong> each carry a unique chemistry, mood, and purpose –\n          so you can understand <strong>where each one shines</strong> instead of treating them all as “just minerals”.\n        </p>\n        <ul class="andara-hero__bullets">\n          <li>\n            <strong>See the emotional “feel” of each source</strong> – ocean, forest, soil, crystal, volcano.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong>Understand the underlying chemistry</strong> – spectrum, sulfate, sodium, reactivity.\n          </li>\n          <li>\n            <strong>Discover which sources are gentle background</strong> and which are\n            <strong>highly catalytic in water</strong>.\n          </li>\n        </ul>\n        <div class="andara-hero__cta-group">\n          <a\n            href="#mineral-sources-comparison"\n            class="andara-hero__cta andara-hero__cta--primary"\n          >\n            Jump to the 5-way comparison\n          </a>\n        </div>\n        <p class="andara-hero__support-text">\n          Or explore the pillars:\n          <a href="#mineral-source-ocean" class="andara-hero__support-link">\n            Ocean\n          </a> ·\n          <a href="#mineral-source-plant" class="andara-hero__support-link">\n            Plant &amp; Seaweed\n          </a> ·\n          <a href="#mineral-source-fulvic" class="andara-hero__support-link">\n            Fulvic/Humic\n          </a> ·\n          <a href="#mineral-source-salt" class="andara-hero__support-link">\n            Sea Salt\n          </a> ·\n          <a href="#mineral-source-mica" class="andara-hero__support-link">\n            Volcanic Mica\n          </a>\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <figure class="andara-hero__media">\n        <div class="andara-hero__media-placeholder">\n          <p>\n            [Hero visual: a panoramic scene with five zones –\n            deep ocean on the left, a green plant/seaweed forest,\n            dark humic soil, bright salt crystals, and a glowing black mica crystal\n            dissolving into structured hexagonal water.]\n          </p>\n        </div>\n        <figcaption class="andara-hero__media-caption">\n          Five mineral “temples” – different origins, different chemistries, one Earth.\n        </figcaption>\n      </figure>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – HERO\n  - Layout:\n    - Two-column layout: left ≈60% text, right ≈40% hero visual.\n    - Desktop: text left, image right. Mobile: stack text above image.\n    - Keep generous padding and breathing space; this is a calm science overview.\n  - Imagery:\n    - Use a panoramic, slightly isometric illustration splitting the canvas into 5 vertical zones:\n      1) Deep ocean water with currents and micro sparkles (trace elements).\n      2) Kelp/seaweed and leafy plants, softly glowing.\n      3) Dark soil/humus strata with tiny glows (fulvic realm).\n      4) Pink/white salt crystals in sunlight.\n      5) Volcanic black mica rock radiating hexagonal light into a water droplet.\n    - Color palette: indigo, turquoise, emerald green, warm brown, soft pink, obsidian, and a touch of gold.\n  - Motion (Framer Motion dictionary):\n    - Apply `ambient-water-ripple` to subtle overlays across the hero background.\n    - Apply `ambient-floating-icons` for small mineral glyphs drifting slowly.\n    - On scroll, use `scroll-fade-up` for headline and bullet list.\n    - On hero media, apply `crystalline-shimmer-slow` loop on the volcanic/mica zone.\n  - Vibe & emotional tone:\n    - Keywords: ["cosmic", "educational", "reassuring", "elemental"].\n    - The hero should feel like opening a mineral atlas, clear and trustworthy, not overwhelming.\n  -->\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       SECTION – FIVE TEMPLES\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-sources-overview"\n    class="andara-section andara-section--overview"\n    aria-label="Overview of Mineral Sources"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-section__inner">\n      <header class="andara-section__header">\n        <h2 class="andara-section__headline">\n          Five Mineral Gateways – One Planet, Five Voices\n        </h2>\n        <p class="andara-section__subline">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            All minerals come from the same Earth – but the way they arrive in your water and your field is radically different.\n          </span>\n          To make sense of the mineral universe, we imagine five “temples”:\n          the <strong>Ocean</strong>, the <strong>Plants &amp; Seaweeds</strong>, the\n          <strong>Fulvic/Humic Realm</strong>, the <strong>Salts</strong>, and the\n          <strong>Volcanic Mica Source</strong>. Each has its own mood, strengths, and limits.\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div\n        class="andara-grid andara-grid--05 andara-grid--temples andara-section__items"\n        aria-label="Five mineral temples"\n      >\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Ocean Minerals</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            <strong>Feel:</strong> vast, rhythmic, motherly.  \n            <strong>Role:</strong> broad-spectrum background – a “liquid plasma” that echoes the mineral balance of blood,\n            with gentle doses and a stable electrolyte field.\n          </p>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Plant &amp; Seaweed Minerals</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            <strong>Feel:</strong> garden, kelp forest, life-wrapped.  \n            <strong>Role:</strong> food-like minerals wrapped in fibers, pigments, and polyphenols – gentle\n            daily background support rather than a sharp water-chemistry tool.\n          </p>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Fulvic &amp; Humic Minerals</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            <strong>Feel:</strong> dark forest floor, alchemical compost.  \n            <strong>Role:</strong> complex organic–mineral meshes that bind and shuttle ions – powerful in soil and\n            ecological regeneration, composition highly dependent on origin.\n          </p>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Sea Salts</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            <strong>Feel:</strong> sun, wind, salt crystals.  \n            <strong>Role:</strong> crystalline sodium-chloride with trace companions – excellent as culinary base\n            and simple electrolyte, limited as dense trace-mineral source.\n          </p>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Volcanic Mica Minerals</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            <strong>Feel:</strong> volcanic spring, deep-crust intelligence.  \n            <strong>Role:</strong> sulfated ionic minerals with high reactivity – clarify water, restructure charge,\n            and carry rare and ultra-trace elements from the planet’s interior.\n          </p>\n        </article>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – OVERVIEW GRID\n  - Layout:\n    - Use a responsive 5-card grid `.andara-grid--05` for the five temples.\n    - Desktop: 5 cards in two rows (3 + 2) or a horizontal scroll strip; mobile: stack cards vertically.\n  - Motion:\n    - Apply `scroll-fade-up-stagger` to `.andara-grid__item` so each card appears sequentially when scrolled into view.\n    - On hover, use `hover-lift-soft` (slight scale and elevation).\n  - Visuals:\n    - Optional small icon for each card:\n      - Ocean: wave icon.\n      - Plant: leaf/kelp icon.\n      - Fulvic: layer / soil icon.\n      - Salt: crystal icon.\n      - Mica: crystal + droplet icon.\n  - Vibe:\n    - Educational, atlas-like. Cards should feel like “entry doors” to deeper sections below.\n  -->\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       SECTION – OCEAN MINERALS\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-source-ocean"\n    class="andara-section andara-section--source andara-section--ocean"\n    aria-label="Ocean Mineral Source"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-section__inner">\n      <header class="andara-section__header">\n        <h2 class="andara-section__headline">\n          1. Ocean Minerals – The Planet’s Liquid Blood\n        </h2>\n        <p class="andara-section__subline">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            Ocean minerals feel like being held by the sea – wide, soft, and quietly regulating.\n          </span>\n          They echo the mineral composition of plasma, offering a broad spectrum in small doses,\n          more like a gentle <strong>mineral background field</strong> than a sharp tool.\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div class="andara-grid andara-grid--02 andara-section__content">\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">What Ocean Minerals Are</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            Deep-ocean mineral solutions are collected from defined marine zones, typically microfiltered rather\n            than chemically extracted. They contain up to <strong>70–80 minerals and trace elements</strong> in ionic form:\n            sodium, chloride, magnesium, calcium, potassium, sulfate and many others in tiny amounts.\n          </p>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            The key is not just how many minerals are present, but how they are proportioned.\n            Ocean minerals mirror the <strong>basic electrolyte architecture</strong> of human plasma, making them feel\n            familiar to biology – a kind of <strong>liquid memory of the planetary ocean</strong>.\n          </p>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Strengths</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li><strong>Broad-spectrum coverage</strong> of many trace elements.</li>\n            <li><strong>Biologically familiar ratios</strong> – similar to plasma.</li>\n            <li><strong>Gentle mineral “background field”</strong> rather than a forceful re-structurer.</li>\n          </ul>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Limitations</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li>\n              <strong>Sodium &amp; chloride dominate</strong> – to get high trace amounts, salt intake also rises.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              <strong>Sulfate is present but not dominant</strong> – weaker flocculation/clarification compared\n              to sulfate-rich volcanic complexes.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Acts more as a <strong>stable electrolyte storage medium</strong> than a catalytic purifier.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <aside class="andara-grid__item">\n          <figure class="andara-figure">\n            <div class="andara-figure__visual">\n              <p>\n                [Illustration: cross-section of ocean with a droplet in front,\n                inside the droplet tiny glowing mineral icons float in smooth currents.]\n              </p>\n            </div>\n            <figcaption class="andara-figure__caption">\n              Ocean minerals: broad-spectrum but gentle – the sea as a softly humming electrolyte field.\n            </figcaption>\n          </figure>\n\n          <div class="andara-highlight-box andara-highlight-box--ocean">\n            <h4 class="andara-highlight-box__title">\n              Ocean Mineral Snapshot\n            </h4>\n            <ul class="andara-highlight-box__list">\n              <li><strong>Spectrum:</strong> Wide</li>\n              <li><strong>Reactivity in water:</strong> Low–medium</li>\n              <li><strong>Sulfate dominance:</strong> Low</li>\n              <li><strong>Sodium load:</strong> High</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p class="andara-highlight-box__note">\n              Ideal as a <strong>background, gentle mineral field</strong>;\n              not designed for strong water purification or restructuring.\n            </p>\n          </div>\n        </aside>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – OCEAN SECTION\n  - Layout:\n    - Two-column layout: left for detailed explanation, right for illustration + highlight box.\n    - On mobile, stack with text first, then visual.\n  - Motion:\n    - Use `scroll-fade-up` on the entire section and `scroll-fade-up-stagger` on bullet lists.\n    - Apply `ambient-ocean-current` subtle background animation (slow moving gradient or particle drift).\n  - Visual:\n    - Emphasize wave shapes and smooth curves around the figure.\n    - Color accent: deep blue and turquoise.\n  -->\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       SECTION – PLANT & SEAWEED\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-source-plant"\n    class="andara-section andara-section--source andara-section--plant"\n    aria-label="Plant and Seaweed Mineral Source"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-section__inner">\n      <header class="andara-section__header">\n        <h2 class="andara-section__headline">\n          2. Plant &amp; Seaweed Minerals – Green Intelligence\n        </h2>\n        <p class="andara-section__subline">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            Plant and seaweed minerals feel like walking through a living garden – mineral intelligence wrapped in fiber and chlorophyll.\n          </span>\n          These are not just ions in water; they come with pigments, polyphenols, and\n          <strong>the subtle codes of living tissues</strong>.\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div class="andara-grid andara-grid--02 andara-section__content">\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">What Plant &amp; Seaweed Minerals Are</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            Plant and seaweed mineral products are extracted from <strong>current biomass</strong>:\n            kelps and marine algae, calcified red algae, and nutrient-dense greens like spirulina, chlorella, or moringa.\n            In these materials, minerals sit inside cells, often bound to\n            <strong>amino acids, polysaccharides, or pigments</strong>.\n          </p>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            Seaweeds excel at <strong>iodine, magnesium, potassium</strong>.  \n            Red algae bring concentrated <strong>Ca–Mg carbonate with many trace elements</strong>.  \n            Greens offer background potassium/magnesium, modest iron, and a spectrum of antioxidants.\n          </p>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Strengths</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li><strong>Food-form minerals</strong> – easy to integrate into meals or supplements.</li>\n            <li>\n              Combination of <strong>minerals + phytonutrients</strong> (polyphenols, phlorotannins, pigments, fibers).\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Excellent as <strong>gentle daily mineral diversity</strong> and iodine or Ca/Mg support.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Limitations</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li>\n              Composition varies with <strong>species, location, and season</strong> – quality and consistency depend on sourcing.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Typically <strong>lower in sulfate and iron</strong> than volcanic sulfate complexes.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Do not significantly <strong>clarify or restructure water</strong> on their own – designed more to feed life than\n              to reshape water chemistry.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <aside class="andara-grid__item">\n          <figure class="andara-figure">\n            <div class="andara-figure__visual">\n              <p>\n                [Illustration: lush kelp forest and leafy greens, with small mineral symbols glowing inside leaves,\n                showing minerals held within living tissues.]\n              </p>\n            </div>\n            <figcaption class="andara-figure__caption">\n              Plant &amp; seaweed minerals: green carriers that mix mineral matrices with fibers, pigments, and life-codes.\n            </figcaption>\n          </figure>\n\n          <div class="andara-highlight-box andara-highlight-box--plant">\n            <h4 class="andara-highlight-box__title">\n              Plant &amp; Seaweed Snapshot\n            </h4>\n            <ul class="andara-highlight-box__list">\n              <li><strong>Spectrum:</strong> Wide but variable</li>\n              <li><strong>Water-structuring effect:</strong> Very low</li>\n              <li><strong>Phytonutrients:</strong> Very high</li>\n              <li><strong>Predictability:</strong> Depends heavily on source</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p class="andara-highlight-box__note">\n              Best seen as <strong>nutritional top-up</strong> – especially for iodine and plant-based calcium/magnesium –\n              not as a primary water-chemistry tool.\n            </p>\n          </div>\n        </aside>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – PLANT SECTION\n  - Layout:\n    - Same two-column layout like the ocean section for consistency.\n  - Motion:\n    - Use `scroll-fade-up` on entire section.\n    - Add `ambient-leaf-sway` (very subtle parallax or sway for leaves/kelp motifs).\n  - Visual:\n    - Dominant colors: emerald green, teal, seaweed brown, with golden highlights.\n    - Use organic, branching shapes suggesting veins or kelp fronds.\n  -->\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       SECTION – FULVIC / HUMIC\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-source-fulvic"\n    class="andara-section andara-section--source andara-section--fulvic"\n    aria-label="Fulvic and Humic Mineral Source"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-section__inner">\n      <header class="andara-section__header">\n        <h2 class="andara-section__headline">\n          3. Fulvic &amp; Humic Minerals – The Dark Alchemy of Decomposition\n        </h2>\n        <p class="andara-section__subline">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            Fulvic and humic minerals feel like the deep forest floor – dark, damp, and full of invisible processes.\n          </span>\n          They arise from <strong>layers of decayed organic matter</strong> transformed over long timescales into\n          complex carbon-based matrices that bind and carry minerals.\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div class="andara-grid andara-grid--02 andara-section__content">\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">What Fulvic &amp; Humic Minerals Are</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            These substances originate from humus, peat, leonardite, and similar deposits where plants, microbes,\n            and sometimes animal inputs have broken down into <strong>dark organic matter</strong>.\n            The key actors – fulvic and humic acids – are not single molecules but\n            <strong>huge clouds of different carbon fragments</strong> that can chelate and shuttle metals.\n          </p>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            Commercial fulvic/humic mineral products concentrate these organic–mineral complexes.\n            They can hold minerals in solution, modulate how they move through soils and systems, and form\n            <strong>bridges between organic and inorganic worlds</strong>.\n          </p>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Strengths</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li>\n              <strong>Broad trace spectrum</strong> combined with organic ligands – a rich, complex matrix.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Strong <strong>binding and chelation capacity</strong>, useful in soil ecology and nutrient cycling.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Acts as a <strong>carrier and mediator</strong> between minerals, microbes, and organic residues.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Limitations</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li>\n              Highly <strong>variable composition</strong> – two deposits can differ significantly in mineral and organic profiles.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Requires <strong>careful sourcing and testing</strong> for heavy metals and contaminants.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Less focused on <strong>specific ionic sulfates</strong> or rare-earth fingerprints compared\n              to volcanic mica-based complexes.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <aside class="andara-grid__item">\n          <figure class="andara-figure">\n            <div class="andara-figure__visual">\n              <p>\n                [Illustration: layered soil strata glowing subtly, with tiny orbs representing minerals\n                woven into a dark, web-like organic network.]\n              </p>\n            </div>\n            <figcaption class="andara-figure__caption">\n              Fulvic/humic minerals: dark matrices that weave together minerals and organic remnants over time.\n            </figcaption>\n          </figure>\n\n          <div class="andara-highlight-box andara-highlight-box--fulvic">\n            <h4 class="andara-highlight-box__title">\n              Fulvic &amp; Humic Snapshot\n            </h4>\n            <ul class="andara-highlight-box__list">\n              <li><strong>Spectrum:</strong> Wide, but highly variable</li>\n              <li><strong>Binding/Chelation:</strong> Very high</li>\n              <li><strong>Water-structuring:</strong> Moderate, indirect</li>\n              <li><strong>Origin clarity:</strong> Often diffuse and ancient</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p class="andara-highlight-box__note">\n              Think of this realm as <strong>the alchemist of soil and water</strong> – powerful, but composition depends on\n              the story of the land it came from.\n            </p>\n          </div>\n        </aside>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – FULVIC SECTION\n  - Layout:\n    - Keep two-column pattern; section background can feel slightly darker than others.\n  - Motion:\n    - Use `ambient-parallax-strata` (slow vertical parallax of layered background).\n    - Apply `scroll-fade-up` and slight `scroll-zoom-in` for the soil illustration.\n  - Visual:\n    - Dominant colors: dark brown, black, deep green with golden sparks.\n    - Use strata lines and root-like branching shapes.\n  -->\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       SECTION – SEA SALTS\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-source-salt"\n    class="andara-section andara-section--source andara-section--salt"\n    aria-label="Sea Salt Mineral Source"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-section__inner">\n      <header class="andara-section__header">\n        <h2 class="andara-section__headline">\n          4. Sea Salts – Crystalline Simplicity with Hidden Guests\n        </h2>\n        <p class="andara-section__subline">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            Sea salts feel like sun and wind crystallized – sharp, bright, and grounding.\n          </span>\n          They are dominated by <strong>sodium chloride</strong>, with a constellation of tiny trace elements\n          hidden inside their crystalline lattice.\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div class="andara-grid andara-grid--02 andara-section__content">\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">What Sea Salts Are</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            Mineral salts like pink Himalayan or Celtic salt come from evaporated seas or deep ancient brines.\n            Chemically, they are mostly <strong>NaCl (sodium chloride)</strong>, with smaller amounts of calcium,\n            magnesium, potassium, sulfate and many trace elements, sometimes including rare-earths and metals.\n          </p>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            Analyses often reveal a surprisingly rich trace fingerprint – but always on the background of a\n            <strong>massive sodium-chloride backbone</strong>. This makes salt perfect for flavor and basic electrolytes,\n            but limited as a dense trace-mineral source.\n          </p>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Strengths</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li><strong>Simple, clear chemistry</strong> – easy to understand and work with.</li>\n            <li><strong>Good base electrolyte</strong> for culinary and hydration purposes.</li>\n            <li>\n              Contains <strong>traces of many elements</strong>, reflecting geologic history of the deposit.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Limitations</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li>\n              To reach meaningful trace-mineral doses, <strong>sodium intake becomes excessive</strong>.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Does not significantly <strong>flocculate or clarify water</strong> beyond raising conductivity.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Better seen as a <strong>culinary crystal</strong> than a focused trace-mineral strategy.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <aside class="andara-grid__item">\n          <figure class="andara-figure">\n            <div class="andara-figure__visual">\n              <p>\n                [Illustration: close-up of pink and white salt crystals,\n                one crystal enlarged to show a big NaCl cube with tiny colored dots inside representing trace elements.]\n              </p>\n            </div>\n            <figcaption class="andara-figure__caption">\n              Sea salts: beautiful crystals with hidden guests – trace minerals embedded in a dominant NaCl structure.\n            </figcaption>\n          </figure>\n\n          <div class="andara-highlight-box andara-highlight-box--salt">\n            <h4 class="andara-highlight-box__title">\n              Sea Salt Snapshot\n            </h4>\n            <ul class="andara-highlight-box__list">\n              <li><strong>NaCl backbone:</strong> Very high</li>\n              <li><strong>Trace mineral richness:</strong> Present but micro-dosed</li>\n              <li><strong>Water purification ability:</strong> Low</li>\n              <li><strong>Best use:</strong> Culinary + basic electrolytes</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p class="andara-highlight-box__note">\n              Excellent for taste and base conductivity – <strong>not</strong> a standalone trace-mineral program.\n            </p>\n          </div>\n        </aside>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – SALT SECTION\n  - Layout:\n    - Follow consistent two-column template.\n  - Motion:\n    - Use `ambient-crystal-glint` on crystal illustration (soft sparkle at edges).\n    - `scroll-fade-up` on cards and lists.\n  - Visual:\n    - Palette: white, pale pink, soft grey, sandy beige.\n    - Shapes: faceted, angular, geometric.\n  -->\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       SECTION – VOLCANIC MICA\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-source-mica"\n    class="andara-section andara-section--source andara-section--mica"\n    aria-label="Volcanic Mica Mineral Source"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-section__inner">\n      <header class="andara-section__header">\n        <h2 class="andara-section__headline">\n          5. Volcanic Mica Minerals – Fire-Born Ionic Intelligence\n        </h2>\n        <p class="andara-section__subline">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            Volcanic mica minerals feel like standing by a hot spring on the flank of a volcano – charged, alive, and deeply intelligent.\n          </span>\n          Here, minerals come from <strong>deep-crust biotite and allied rocks</strong>, transformed into\n          a fully <strong>sulfated ionic form</strong> that is highly reactive in water.\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div class="andara-grid andara-grid--02 andara-section__content">\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">What Volcanic Mica Minerals Are</h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            This source begins with <strong>black mica / biotite and related volcanic minerals</strong>, carrying deep-crust\n            signatures including iron, magnesium, aluminum, calcium and rare-earth elements.\n            Through a controlled process, these are converted into a liquid\n            <strong>ionic sulfate complex</strong> – all minerals dissolved, charged, and ready to interact with water.\n          </p>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            In water, such complexes do more than “add minerals”.\n            The combination of <strong>high sulfate</strong> and <strong>multivalent ions</strong> (Fe³⁺, Al³⁺, Mg²⁺, Ca²⁺)\n            enables strong <strong>flocculation and coagulation</strong> of impurities and distinct shifts in\n            <strong>charge distribution, ORP, and turbidity</strong>. Water can move toward a clearer,\n            more structured, <strong>EZ-like state</strong> at specific concentration ranges.\n          </p>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Strengths</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li>\n              <strong>High sulfate dominance</strong> – powerful driver for clarification and charge structuring in water.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              <strong>Rich mineral spectrum</strong> including <strong>rare and ultra-trace elements</strong>.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Acts as a <strong>catalyst in water</strong> – small dose, big structural effect on clarity and charge.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n\n          <h4 class="andara-grid__subtitle">Limitations</h4>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list">\n            <li>\n              Needs <strong>precise dosing and clear intended use</strong> – especially in regulatory contexts.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Strongly ionic and reactive – not a soft, food-like mineral; more a\n              <strong>precision water-structuring tool</strong>.\n            </li>\n            <li>\n              Requires rigorous <strong>quality control and certification</strong>.\n            </li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <aside class="andara-grid__item">\n          <figure class="andara-figure">\n            <div class="andara-figure__visual">\n              <p>\n                [Illustration: a black mica crystal at the base, with glowing lines rising into a water droplet\n                filled with hexagonal patterns; small particles in the water clump and fall out as the droplet clarifies.]\n              </p>\n            </div>\n            <figcaption class="andara-figure__caption">\n              Volcanic mica minerals: deep-crust signatures in a sulfated ionic form that clarifies and structures water.\n            </figcaption>\n          </figure>\n\n          <div class="andara-highlight-box andara-highlight-box--mica">\n            <h4 class="andara-highlight-box__title">\n              Volcanic Mica Snapshot\n            </h4>\n            <ul class="andara-highlight-box__list">\n              <li><strong>Sulfate dominance:</strong> Very high</li>\n              <li><strong>Water-structuring &amp; flocculation:</strong> Very high</li>\n              <li><strong>Rare-elements fingerprint:</strong> Distinct and rich</li>\n              <li><strong>Sodium load:</strong> Very low (in well-designed complexes)</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p class="andara-highlight-box__note">\n              Best understood as a <strong>precision mineral instrument for water and fields</strong>,\n              not a generic “mineral supplement”.\n            </p>\n          </div>\n        </aside>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – MICA SECTION\n  - Layout:\n    - Maintain two-column pattern; consider slightly more dramatic framing (e.g., subtle dark-to-light gradient).\n  - Motion:\n    - Use `ambient-volcanic-glow` around the mica crystal visual.\n    - Apply `ambient-crystalline-shimmer` to hexagonal patterns in the water droplet.\n    - Use `scroll-fade-up-stagger` for strengths/limitations lists.\n  - Visual:\n    - Palette: obsidian black, deep indigo, electric turquoise, gold accents.\n    - Shapes: tetrahedrons, hexagons, crystalline grids.\n  -->\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       SECTION – COMPARISON GRID\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-sources-comparison"\n    class="andara-section andara-section--comparison"\n    aria-label="Comparative Overview of Mineral Sources"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-section__inner">\n      <header class="andara-section__header">\n        <h2 class="andara-section__headline">\n          One View – Five Sources Side by Side\n        </h2>\n        <p class="andara-section__subline">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            To really feel the difference, it helps to see all five sources next to each other.\n          </span>\n          This comparison grid isn’t about “good or bad” – it’s about matching the\n          <strong>right mineral voice</strong> to the <strong>right job</strong>:\n          gentle background, food-like support, dark alchemy, crystal simplicity, or volcanic precision.\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div\n        class="andara-grid andara-grid--05 andara-grid--comparison andara-section__items"\n        aria-label="Mineral source comparison cards"\n      >\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Ocean Minerals</h3>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list andara-grid__list--comparison">\n            <li><strong>Spectrum:</strong> ★★★★☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Reactivity in water:</strong> ★★☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Sulfate dominance:</strong> ★★☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Sodium load:</strong> ★★★★☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Gentle background mineral field</li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Plant &amp; Seaweed</h3>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list andara-grid__list--comparison">\n            <li><strong>Spectrum:</strong> ★★★★☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Reactivity in water:</strong> ★☆☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Phytonutrients:</strong> ★★★★★</li>\n            <li><strong>Predictability:</strong> ★★☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Food-form mineral and iodine support</li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Fulvic &amp; Humic</h3>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list andara-grid__list--comparison">\n            <li><strong>Spectrum:</strong> ★★★★☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Binding/Chelation:</strong> ★★★★★</li>\n            <li><strong>Water-structuring:</strong> ★★☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Variability:</strong> ★★★★★</li>\n            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Soil/terrain alchemy &amp; ion shuttling</li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Sea Salts</h3>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list andara-grid__list--comparison">\n            <li><strong>Spectrum:</strong> ★★☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Reactivity:</strong> ★★☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Sodium load:</strong> ★★★★★</li>\n            <li><strong>Practical supplement range:</strong> ★★☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Taste &amp; basic electrolytes</li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">Volcanic Mica</h3>\n          <ul class="andara-grid__list andara-grid__list--comparison">\n            <li><strong>Spectrum:</strong> ★★★★★</li>\n            <li><strong>Reactivity &amp; structuring:</strong> ★★★★★</li>\n            <li><strong>Sulfate dominance:</strong> ★★★★★</li>\n            <li><strong>Sodium load:</strong> ★☆☆☆☆</li>\n            <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Precision water clarification &amp; structuring</li>\n          </ul>\n        </article>\n      </div>\n\n      <footer class="andara-section__footer">\n        <p class="andara-section__summary">\n          <span class="andara-text-lead">\n            Organic matter is simply mineral matter rearranged by life.\n          </span>\n          To understand water and biology at depth, we start with the minerals themselves –\n          and with the <strong>source story</strong> behind each mineral stream we invite into our systems.\n        </p>\n      </footer>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – COMPARISON GRID\n  - Layout:\n    - 5 card grid `.andara-grid--comparison`; desktop can show all five in a row or a 3+2 layout.\n    - Mobile: horizontal scroll cards or stacked vertical layout.\n  - Motion:\n    - `scroll-fade-up-stagger` on cards.\n    - Optional `ambient-rating-glow` for the volcanic mica stars to subtly highlight its distinct profile (without feeling salesy).\n  - Visual:\n    - Use small star icons for the rating rows.\n    - Subtle colored border or background tint per source (blue for ocean, green for plant, brown for fulvic, pink for salt, indigo/gold for mica).\n  -->\n\n  <!-- =========================\n       SECTION – NEXT STEPS\n  ========================== -->\n  <section\n    id="mineral-sources-next"\n    class="andara-section andara-section--next-steps"\n    aria-label="Next steps and related pages"\n  >\n    <div class="andara-section__inner">\n      <header class="andara-section__header">\n        <h2 class="andara-section__headline">\n          Where to Go Next in the Mineral Library\n        </h2>\n        <p class="andara-section__subline">\n          You’ve met the five main mineral gateways. Now you can dive deeper into how they relate to\n          <strong>water structuring, bioelectricity, and the terrain model</strong>.\n        </p>\n      </header>\n\n      <div\n        class="andara-grid andara-grid--03 andara-grid--next-steps andara-section__items"\n        aria-label="Suggested next pages"\n      >\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">\n            Mineral Science · Sulfate Chemistry\n          </h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            Discover why sulfate plays such a unique role in water clarification, gel structuring, and\n            charge layering – and how it connects volcanic mineral sources to biological terrain.\n          </p>\n          <p class="andara-grid__link">\n            <a href="/science/mineral-sulfate-chemistry">\n              Explore sulfate chemistry &rarr;\n            </a>\n          </p>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">\n            Water Science · Structured &amp; EZ Water\n          </h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            Go deeper into structured/EZ water, hydration layers, and how different mineral regimes\n            influence the way water holds charge and information.\n          </p>\n          <p class="andara-grid__link">\n            <a href="/science/water-structured-ez">\n              Explore structured water &rarr;\n            </a>\n          </p>\n        </article>\n\n        <article class="andara-grid__item">\n          <h3 class="andara-grid__title">\n            Terrain Model · Mineral &amp; Microbiome\n          </h3>\n          <p class="andara-grid__text">\n            See how mineral availability forms the invisible scaffolding for enzymes, microbes, and mucosal surfaces –\n            the true roots of what we call “gut health”.\n          </p>\n          <p class="andara-grid__link">\n            <a href="/science/terrain-minerals-microbiome">\n              Explore minerals &amp; terrain &rarr;\n            </a>\n          </p>\n        </article>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </section>\n\n  <!--\n  REPLIT / MOTION LAYOUT PROMPT – NEXT STEPS\n  - Layout:\n    - 3-card grid for related pages.\n  - Motion:\n    - Use `scroll-fade-up-stagger` on cards.\n    - `hover-lift-soft` + `hover-glow-border` for card hover states.\n  - Visual:\n    - Keep this section lighter and optimistic, with subtle Andara accent colors.\n  -->\n\n</main>	{"components": ["andara-page", "andara-page--science", "andara-hero", "andara-hero--science", "andara-hero__inner", "andara-hero__content", "andara-hero__label", "andara-hero__headline", "andara-hero__subline", "andara-text-lead", "andara-hero__bullets", "andara-hero__cta-group", "andara-hero__cta", "andara-hero__cta--primary", "andara-hero__support-text", "andara-hero__support-link", "andara-hero__media", "andara-hero__media-placeholder", "andara-hero__media-caption", "andara-section", "andara-section--overview", "andara-section__inner", "andara-section__header", "andara-section__headline", "andara-section__subline"